The paper focuses on the performance and resilience of a cyber-physical control system (CPCS) with attack detection and reactive attack mitigation in the context of power grids. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the cs.SY (Systems and Control) sub-category. Additionally, the paper addresses the problem of deriving an optimal sequence of false data injection attacks, which involves decision-making and optimization, indicating that it could also belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. The paper also discusses the impact of false positives and negatives in detecting attacks, which is related to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category. The use of Q-learning with linear and non-linear function approximators suggests that the paper could also belong to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-categories.
